{
  "texts": [
    "Since no bacterial host could be determined for the qnrS1carrying plasmid in sample A, we investigated the use of methylation motifs to associate it to a potential host (Figures 1C, 3).",
    "Initially, neither the metagenomic pipeline nor the NanoMotif \"include_contig\" command assigned the qnrS1-carrying plasmid to any bin.",
    "However, visualization of methylation motifs indicated that the methylation patterns of three unbinned plasmids, among which the qnrS1-carrying plasmid, resembled the pattern of the E. coli and the K. pneumoniae bins.",
    "Still, the motifs TG6mANNNNNNCTTT (and AA6mAGNNNNNNTYA, representing its reverse complement) and GC5mCGGC were methylated in the qnrS1-carrying plasmid and in E. coli, but not in K. pneumoniae, indicating the plasmid likely belongs to E. coli (Figure 3A).",
    "In contrast, methylation signatures for a plasmid contig binned as E. coli (contig 866, Figure 3A) clustered more closely with the K. pneumoniae bin, as it was not methylated for the motifs mentioned above."
  ]
}